  "text": "FCs tend to use attitude markers more frequently than MCs and the difference is statistically significant (Table 3) . By using attitude markers, candidates try to interact more with their audience and to express a position and pull the audience into a conspiracy of agreement to the extent that it is often difficult to dispute these judgments (Hyland, 2005: 180) . This point is illustrated in 4 (a, b). s lmand n among agers \"Unfortunately, the level of health is very low among agers in Iran\" (FC) In these two examples the MC and the FC have used attitude adverbs (khoshbakht neh, moteassef neh) to signal assumptions of shared attitudes and values. Sometimes, the candidates have used intensifiers (kheili and besy r) to convey their attitudes. The following two examples show this kind of manipulation: 5 a) albatteh yek matlab hast ke kheili j lebeh ke ofcourse one subject is that very interesting which \"Of course, there is an issue, very interesting, which …\" (MC) 5 b) n chizi ke besy r j lebeh ine ke that thing that very interesting this that \"What is very interesting is that …\" (FC) In 5(a, b), both candidates have employed the structure \"intensifier + attitude adjective (j leb)\" to convey their attitudes and to persuade the audience [CITATION_1] .",
